Similarly for a 5k runner

00:00:57.390 --> 00:01:02.109
it takes quite a lot of time to recover
from say it 2k or a 3k run or a

00:01:02.109 --> 00:01:05.339
2 mile run if you if you training for a
5 mile race

00:01:05.339 --> 00:01:08.229
you might be better off doing 4
hundreds or 8 hundreds or 1

00:01:08.229 --> 00:01:11.149
thousand meter repeats in that in in
that fashion

00:01:11.149 --> 00:01:12.329
a little bit faster.

00:01:12.329 --> 00:01:15.350
So the Tempo run is associated more with a
heart marathon,

00:01:15.350 --> 00:01:16.340
and the marathon.

00:01:16.340 --> 00:01:20.010
So if you would training for a marathon,
a Tempo run might be something like

00:01:20.010 --> 00:01:23.879
a 9 miles or 8 miles at your
marathon pace.

00:01:23.879 --> 00:01:27.449
And it's that shorter distance of what you're able to recover

00:01:27.449 --> 00:01:28.450
from that

00:01:28.450 --> 00:01:32.829
a very quickly the day off
or even maybe two days after

00:01:32.829 --> 00:01:36.389
and be able to get back to easy running
immediately and to be able to get back

00:01:36.389 --> 00:01:41.049
to quality training within one or two
days. And so if you are not able to do

00:01:41.049 --> 00:01:43.729
that then there's two ways to go with
that is due

00:01:43.729 --> 00:01:47.320
shorter Tempo runs so as a marathon runner and you might only do a 6 mile Tempo run

00:01:47.320 --> 00:01:49.090
or a 5 mile Tempo run

00:01:49.090 --> 00:01:53.560
or to fractionalize your Tempo run, which
is something I find very very useful so

00:01:53.560 --> 00:01:57.080
as a marathon runner you might wanna
run a 15 mile Tempo run which would

00:01:57.080 --> 00:01:59.640
be ideal for your marathon distance but

00:01:59.640 --> 00:02:03.049
takes a lot of emotional mental energy
and it takes a long time to recover from

00:02:03.049 --> 00:02:03.600
that.

00:02:03.600 --> 00:02:06.980
So you might be able to fractionalize
that you might do something like four

00:02:06.980 --> 00:02:08.390
or 5 x 5K

